Law, in this week, functioned less as a limit on power than as a set of tools to be aimed. The administration designated \'93Antifa\'94 as a domestic terrorist organization through an executive memo, despite the lack of a legal framework for such designations. A National Security Presidential Memorandum redefined beliefs\'97such as being \'93anti\uc0\u8209 Christian\'94 or holding \'93extremism on migration\'94\'97as indicators of violence, directing the government to investigate and disrupt groups whose members held such views. The Justice Department opened a RICO investigation into George Soros\'92 Open Society Foundations, echoing Trump\'92s public calls for Soros to be jailed. These moves did not simply expand enforcement; they recast ideological opposition as a security threat. Belief itself became suspect.\
