The same pattern appeared in high\uc0\u8209 profile prosecutions. Former national security adviser John Bolton was indicted on 18 counts under the Espionage Act for mishandling classified information, including diary entries and emails later hacked by Iran. Career prosecutors brought the case, but Bolton and his lawyers framed it as retaliation for his critical memoir of Trump. The Justice Department also indicted New York attorney general Letitia James and former FBI director James Comey, both long\u8209 standing political adversaries of the president. At the same time, the administration refiled a $15 billion defamation suit against the New York Times and its reporters, after an earlier complaint was dismissed, and Trump personally sued the paper again over coverage of his finances and television show. Together, these actions signaled that those who challenged the president\'97through oversight, investigation, or reporting\'97could expect to face the full weight of criminal and civil law. The chill was deliberate.\
