Universities and student media found themselves on the front lines of this struggle over information and memory. The administration offered a \'93Compact for Academic Excellence\'94 that promised favorable federal funding in exchange for restrictions on diversity, equity, and inclusion programs and limits on international student enrollment. Brown University, the University of Pennsylvania, and the University of Southern California all rejected the offer, citing threats to academic freedom and governance autonomy. In Texas, a new state law disbanded faculty senates at public universities, centralizing power in administrators and a hand\uc0\u8209 picked advisory board. At Indiana University, administrators ordered the student newspaper to cease its print edition and fired the director of student media who resisted, prompting accusations of censorship. These moves used financial and administrative levers to narrow the space for independent thought and student journalism. The classroom and newsroom were both targets.\
