The administration also worked to reshape national memory and symbolism. Trump issued a Columbus Day proclamation that cast Christopher Columbus as an \'93original American hero\'94 and denounced modern critiques of his legacy, aligning the state\'92s narrative with white Christian nationalism. He proposed a triumphal arch on the Potomac\'97the \'93Arc de Trump\'94\'97and a privately funded $250 million White House ballroom, projects that would literally inscribe his name and image into the capital\'92s landscape. At the same time, the administration moved to sell the Wilbur J. Cohen Federal Building, home to murals celebrating the Social Security Act\'92s promise of security and equality, and pursued executive orders banning diversity, equity, and inclusion language in federally funded anti\uc0\u8209 trafficking work. Together, these actions elevated conquest and hierarchy while erasing or constraining narratives of egalitarianism and justice. What could not be celebrated was pushed aside.\
