Elections and representation were not spared. In North Carolina, Republican leaders announced plans to redraw congressional maps mid\uc0\u8209 decade to add another Republican seat, in a state already tilted 10\'964 in their favor despite an even partisan split. The new map was expected to reduce Black representation and was timed alongside a Supreme Court case, Louisiana v. Callais, that could weaken Section 2 of the Voting Rights Act. The Court heard arguments in multiple formulations of that case, with the conservative majority appearing open to narrowing the ability to challenge racially discriminatory maps. Trump, for his part, pressured Republican\u8209 led states to redraw their maps to eliminate Democratic districts. In Arizona, the attorney general demanded that Speaker Johnson swear in Adelita Grijalva and later filed suit when he refused, arguing that voters were being denied representation. These moves pointed toward a future in which minority rule could be locked in through legalistic redistricting and procedural obstruction. The forms of democracy remained; the substance thinned.\
